---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import { Code } from "astro-expressive-code/components";
import CodeTabs from "../../components/CodeTabs.astro";
---

<DocsLayout title="Core Concepts">
  <h1>Core Concepts</h1>

  <h2>Nodes</h2>
  <p>
    Nodes are the primary entities. Node types are defined in a
    <code>.proto</code> file with a stable numeric <code>type_id</code>, and
    the SDK stores payloads keyed by protobuf <code>field_id</code> &mdash;
    never by name. This makes field renames a no-op.
  </p>
  <Code code={`// schema.proto
message Task {
  option (entdb.type_id) = 1;
  string title = 1;
  string status = 2;   // field_id is the wire key
}`} lang="proto" />
  <p>
    Compile with <code>protoc --python_out</code> and register the generated
    module with <code>register_proto_schema(schema_pb2)</code>. The
    <code>type_id</code> and <code>field_id</code> numbers are immutable; the
    names are not.
  </p>

  <h2>Edges</h2>
  <p>Edges are unidirectional relationships between nodes. Edge types define which node types can be connected and whether ACLs propagate:</p>
  <Code code={`AssignedTo = EdgeTypeDef(edge_id=1, name="AssignedTo",
    from_type=Task, to_type=User,
    propagate_share=False)  # assigning doesn't share ACL

HasComment = EdgeTypeDef(edge_id=2, name="HasComment",
    from_type=Task, to_type=Comment,
    propagate_share=True)   # sharing task shares comments`} lang="plaintext" />
  <p><code>propagate_share=True</code> makes the edge "structural" &mdash; child nodes inherit access from the parent.</p>

  <h2>Tenants</h2>
  <p>
    Every operation requires a <code>tenant_id</code>. Each tenant gets its
    own SQLite database file (optionally encrypted with SQLCipher). Tenants
    are fully isolated &mdash; no cross-tenant queries, no shared tables.
    Crypto-shred a tenant by destroying its data encryption key and the
    on-disk file becomes unreadable.
  </p>
  <Code code={`# Different tenants, completely separate data
acme = db.tenant("acme").actor(Actor.user("alice"))
globex = db.tenant("globex").actor(Actor.user("bob"))`} lang="plaintext" />

  <h2>Actors</h2>
  <p>
    Every operation requires an <code>Actor</code> &mdash; the typed identity
    performing the action. Use the constructors instead of raw strings.
  </p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`from entdb_sdk import Actor

Actor.user("alice")        # user:alice
Actor.group("eng")         # group:eng
Actor.service("ingest-api") # service:ingest-api`}
    go={`import "github.com/elloloop/tenant-shard-db/sdk/go/entdb"

entdb.UserActor("alice")          // user:alice
entdb.GroupActor("eng")           // group:eng
entdb.ServiceActor("ingest-api")  // service:ingest-api

// Parse a "kind:id" string back into an Actor
a, err := entdb.ParseActor("user:alice")`}
  />
  <table>
    <tr><th>Constructor</th><th>Wire form</th><th>Use for</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>Actor.user(id)</code></td><td><code>user:id</code></td><td>Human principals</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>Actor.group(id)</code></td><td><code>group:id</code></td><td>Shared team identities</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>Actor.service(id)</code></td><td><code>service:id</code></td><td>Backend services / system accounts</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h2>WAL-First Event Sourcing</h2>
  <p>
    EntDB is WAL-first: the WAL (Kafka, Kinesis, Pub/Sub, SQS, or S3) is the
    source of truth. SQLite is a materialized view that can be rebuilt by
    replaying events. <strong>Every</strong> mutation &mdash; including GDPR
    deletes, ACL changes, and ownership transfers &mdash; is appended to the
    WAL.
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li><code>plan.commit()</code> &rarr; operations serialized as a transaction event</li>
    <li>Event appended to the WAL backend</li>
    <li>Server returns <code>Receipt</code> with <code>stream_position</code></li>
    <li>The Applier consumes WAL events and applies them to per-tenant SQLite idempotently</li>
    <li>Reads come from SQLite &mdash; the SDK auto-tracks offsets so reads after writes are consistent by default</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Atomic Transactions (Plan)</h2>
  <p>
    Multiple operations are batched into a single atomic transaction via the
    <code>Plan</code> builder. <code>plan.create()</code> accepts proto
    messages directly.
  </p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`import schema_pb2
from entdb_sdk import Actor

scope = db.tenant("acme").actor(Actor.user("alice"))
plan = scope.plan()
plan.create(schema_pb2.Task(title="New Task"), as_="task")
plan.create(schema_pb2.Comment(body="First comment"), as_="comment")
plan.edge_create("HasComment", from_="$task.id", to="$comment.id")
result = await plan.commit()
# All three operations succeed or fail together`}
    go={`scope := client.Tenant("acme").Actor(entdb.UserActor("alice"))
plan := scope.Plan()
plan.Create(&schema.Task{Title: "New Task"}, entdb.As("task"))
plan.Create(&schema.Comment{Body: "First comment"}, entdb.As("comment"))
entdb.EdgeCreate[*schema.HasComment](plan, "$task.id", "$comment.id")
result, err := plan.Commit(ctx)
// All three operations succeed or fail together`}
  />
  <p>The <code>as_</code> parameter creates an alias for referencing the created node in subsequent operations (<code>$task.id</code>).</p>

  <h2>Read-after-Write Consistency</h2>
  <p>
    The SDK automatically tracks the last observed stream offset per tenant
    (<code>db._last_offsets</code>) and forwards it on subsequent reads, so
    you get read-after-write by default. For explicit control:
  </p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`# Option 1: Wait during commit
result = await plan.commit(wait_applied=True)

# Option 2: Wait on a specific read
task = await scope.get(Task, node_id,
                       after_offset=result.receipt.stream_position)`}
    go={`result, err := plan.Commit(ctx)

// Explicit wait — block until the applier has caught up to the
// stream position the commit returned. After this, all reads on
// any scope for this tenant see the new data.
client.WaitForOffset(ctx, "acme", "user:alice",
    result.Receipt.StreamPosition, 5_000)

task, err := entdb.Get[*shop.Task](ctx, scope, nodeID)`}
  />

  <h2>Schema Registry</h2>
  <p>Type definitions are registered in a <code>SchemaRegistry</code>. The registry generates a fingerprint (SHA-256 hash) used for:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Deployment safety</strong>: server rejects writes with mismatched fingerprint</li>
    <li><strong>CI checks</strong>: <code>entdb check</code> validates compatibility before deploy</li>
    <li><strong>Schema evolution</strong>: tracks what changed between versions</li>
  </ul>
</DocsLayout>
